{"key":"processedPost-12689990","value":{"id":12689990,"first":12672191,"last":12690264,"when":1275739778,"utime":"06/05/10 03:09 PM","cleanedPost":"Confirmation of what?&nbsp; The amount of gypsum?&nbsp; If you're using ten percent gypsum by weight, that's plenty.&nbsp; I've been experimenting with using less gypsum on my shiitake blocks, and so far I haven't seen any reduction in performance until I get less than 5% by volume, which is around 2 1/2% by weight.&nbsp; Bear in mind that's using hardwoods, which may be somewhat higher in minerals than what you're using for substrate.<br />Gypsum supplies calcium and sulfur, both of which are essential for good fruitbody formation.&nbsp; Using too much doesn't really hurt, it just doesn't help to use more than is needed by the mycelium.&nbsp; However, if your substrate is lacking these minerals, failure to use enough gypsum will impact yields substantially.<br />RR"}}